<response>None</response>< Review>
First time trying out this location since I've had such s huge craving for delicious sushi. I admit, I want expecting much since it's on Burlingame Avenue. For some reason, a good amount of food spots on that street tend to disappoint me so I try to find hole in the wall places with good reviews. So glad I decided to take some chance.

The staff were quite friendly and patient. They followed CDC guidelines very well which is well appreciated. I was impressed with the imported selection of Japanese whiskies and will definitely try their flights on my next visit. The food was quite delicious. Ordered the surf and turf roll, the firefighter and the 007. All good choices along with their omakase which I may skip since the rolls tasted amazing! Dessert was pretty basic with the options of green tea ice cream and mochi which I will probably go some place else for dessert on the Avenue.

Overall,  10/10. Kudos to management and the staff for creating a safe environment for indoor dining. Can't wait to visit again soon< /Review>

< text>
The best sushi and saki experiences of my life.  I didn't go there planning on writing of our experience, so didnt keep track of all the sushies and the Sakis we had.  The specific items I remember were.  3 types of sashimi Toro  hamachi, salmon and blue fin. Eaten in a specific order with a sip of saki to be held on the tongue for 3 seconds.  Wow!  Stanley the owner was helpful and very informative on our various dishes and the proper way to maximize their enjoyment.  We were there on a Sunday evening so the place wasn't busy and I'm sure afforded Stanley more opportunity to guide us.   Not that we were new to sushi far from it.  What we got from Stanley was not only the order to eat a dish but the flavors to look for, the mouth feel to experience, when to eat something in one bite or not, when to dip into the soy sauce etc.  The bluefin tuna collar was exceptional. We had at least 8 dishes all were outstanding. Then the topper was the Japanese whiskeys we sampled.  I originally said at the start of this review one of the best sushi and saki experiences and changed it to THE BEST.< /text>

< Text>
While the menu is very attractive, what I quickly discovered is that I Prive was bland. The sushi rice is an unusually large grained, bland variety, and the rice to topping/filling ratio is very heavy on the rice side. The fish is sitting in the refrigeration case unwrapped and drying out. The flavors in seasonings and sauces were bland. The sake was over-priced for the brands that were on offer. I didn't hear any Japanese spoken by anyone there, but rather both counter and wait-staff were speaking Chinese. Bottom line: Unless you're looking for what this restauranteur considers a trendy vibe, you'll likely find mediocre value and be disappointed, especially with the flavors and textures.< /Text>

<Time>1417469920342<//Time>< Rating>

<text>I had a fantastic experience here at I Priv√©. 5 stars for service/experience, 4 stars for food.

I came here with a girlfriend on a Wednesday night. We had reservations and were sat immediately. The service was INCREDIBLY attentive, within minutes of being seated we were asked for drinks, asked if we had questions on the menu, etc. All night long the servers were constantly by our side, giving suggestions, answering questions, etc.

We ordered the Joy's Sunamono, the Tony & Kathy, the i Belushi, the Josh, the Jada, the Danielle, and the Spring & Rene. The big hits were the Joy's, the Tony & Kathy, the i Belushi, and the Jada. The Josh was OK, and I could have lived without the Spring & Rene and the Danielle.

Joy's Sunamono: Great ratio of fish to other stuff. Really good flavors, great starter, not very heavy.

Tony & Kathy: The black cod was perfectly cooked, really nice skin on it.

i Belushi: Easily my favorite dish of the night. I would be happy eating this every day for the rest of my life. It absolutely blew the night away. The chef came out and talked to us and told us how to eat the dish, first trying it plain, second trying it on a chip, and third trying it with a sake pairing. He recommended a sake to pair with it, and it was absurdly good. I cannot recommend this dish enough.

Josh: We did two spicy tuna, two crab. It was good but incredibly greasy for what it was.

Jada: A great combination of smoky and sweet

Danielle: Definitely would have been fine NOT eating this. It was very garlicky and wasn't really anything special to write home about, unlike most of the previous dishes we'd had. Not a great way to end the meal.

Spring & Rene: The salmon belly itself was perfectly cooked and delicious, but the chocolate sauce and other accoutrements weren't good at all. Again, not a great end to the meal.

We didn't get dessert so no comments there. The cocktails were good but very sweet, the sake was straight on though, as was the whiskey tasting.

Overall, I'd be happy to come back. There are still so many items on the menu I'd love to explore, and most of what we had was fabulous.</text>< pics>

< review>
We visited on a Saturday evening, without reservations, and were able to be immediately seated at the sushi bar even though they were quite busy.  We ordered a deluxe sushi dinner, a spider roll and an udon soup.  One of the first things we noticed when we began eating the sushi was they they didn't use seasoned rice.  The spider roll was okay, but we've had better at other places.  The deluxe sushi dinner included 2 pieces of salmon (Sake) and 2 pieces of tuna (Maguro), which were both fresh.  But the snapper (Tai) on the nigiri was not fresh and the yellowtail (Hamachi) on the nigiri was soggy.  As part of the deluxe sushi we also got a cucumber roll (Kappamaki) and a California roll.  The cucumber roll appeared to have been pre-made, since the nori wrapping was also soggy and broken.  The California roll was very average.  Overall, we were very disappointed.  Service was good, but the food was only average, and the restaurant was very noisy.  Considering that we can get excellent traditional sushi in Burlingame at Sakae, and non-traditional rolls at Barracuda, it is unlikely that we'll return to I Prive'.<//review>

< review>
This place is a gem! Flavorful & high quality ingredients. We had Lunch Packet (similar to tamale but made w rice & veggies & wrapped in banana leaf) and Pol Roti (bread + side dishes). We chose sambal (addictive spicy minced goodness), lentil curry, jackfruit. Everything was flavorful & did not taste greasy! Will be eating their food regularly going forward!< /review>

<user_name>Lisa Ratnavira<//user_name>< Review>
Love this authentic Sri Lankan cuisine!!< /Review>
< GmapID>
0x80dd28309f5b88f5:0x527c5a02fe0dc071< /GmapID>

<Rating>5<//Rating>< user_id>
105752952950814313225< /user_id>
<name>Raz & Imbri P<//name><gmapID>0x80dd28309f5b88f5:0x527c5a02fe0dc071</gmapID><Review>Neither of us had tried Sri Lankan food before, so when we crossed the strip-mall parking lot to the unassuming little restaurant almost tucked away in the corner, we had no idea at all what to expect. The simple, no-frills dining room and long warming tray display of unfamiliar dishes along the front next to the register told us that any longevity for this business would rely entirely on the food. The aromas were incredible, though, so we had instantly high hopes.

Our hopes were slightly dashed when we heard that none of the mutton dishes were still on the menu, but Raz ordered one beef and one veg dish from those on display with some rice, and I put in an order for Godamba Roti, and asked for suggestions on which meat and veg curry to pair it with. Godamba Roti appears to be a crepe-like flatbread that has an indescribably complex flavor. Alas, I did not write down any of the names of the sides and curries, and I couldn't even remember what I'd actually ordered when it came to the table. All I did know was that I'd never had anything else quite like it. Every single dish we had defied explanation, being simply too rich with complex and complementary flavors. One thing was certain, though, when the staff promised a dish was spicy, it pleasantly packed on the scovilles. Rice N' Spice was definitely one of those places we would come back halfway across the country to try again.< /Review>< Pics>
None< /Pics>

I explain than why did you give me the small curry he says ok give me the small and I'll bring you a large curry. Unfortunately our facility is not as big as we would like, but we have opened up 3 doors to do feed back to help accommodate the space. If you have any suggestions on how we can best utilize the space, please let me know. We love feed back from our families on how we can improve. We have a 4:1 ratio and all the classes are 30 minutes long. Out of those 30 minutes, 27 minutes is designated to teaching and 3 minutes for giving feed back.  Again, we do apologize in regards to your experience here at Aqua Tots and we wish you and your family the very best!"}< /resp><user_name>Anna Chateau< /user_name><Pictures>None</Pictures><Rating>1< /Rating><gmapID>0x80d945976f8d1405:0x6f5c04bfd4c39139< /gmapID><text>Edit: unfortunately the dialogue with the swim school has exhausted itself.

< Text>
Aqua tots is great. My child has been taking lessons here now for a few years.

I do like the very small class size, and often the instructors double up, so the ratio is even better. The good ratio allows for better interaction with the students.

I am always a little baffled at the end of the class. When they come out of the water the the teacher meets you by the door with your child. They then explain in very stringent technical jargon about what your child is doing well or not doing well. I honestly have no idea what their butterfly stroke is supposed to look like, or how they are supposed to practice it at home. They always tell you that, and i just nod. No idea what they are talking about.

Overall its a quality swimming school at a very reasonable price. Highly recommend.<//Text>

<rating>5<//rating><user>106016607046361920442</user><Review>It's expensive. Get over it. They are worth it. Update (About 9 lessons): My daughter jumped off the edge of our pool (deep end), surfaced and swam back to the edge of the pool.  We decided to let her try after she "graduated" level 3. She's not an Olympic swimmer with any sort of form but mission accomplished in my book. My son isn't making as much progress but he's only 3 and has trouble staying on task during class. Considering private lessons.

Big lesson learned so far is that if you have two kids in a 4 kid group class that have trouble paying attention it's hard (read: impossible, class is worthless) for the single instructor to keep things moving, it's not the instructors fault, they'll work with you to find a solution. I see they've recently added a "Master Instructor" that floats between active classes that really helps in this situation. If your kid isn't paying attention (like my son) consider other options like private or semi private lessons.</Review></record>

< review>
I highly recommend that you avoid this place unless you want to be robbed, we bought a beautiful Chrysler 300 in June 2017 and it's been in the shop atleast once a month sometimes even twice a month ever since, my husband is almost done paying it off already but it's parked and can't be driven because it's been overheating among other issues, Albert the "salesman" personally went on the test drive and told us the vehicle had passed a full engine inspection. Such a lie, I've been saving all of my receipts for all the repairs because one day they will come in handy against blue diamond, for anyone interested you can contact the DMV they have a special unit that deals with car dealers like blue diamond, they even have an online form that you can fill out and upload your proof, they will contact you and go from there. I'm in this process as we speak, I'm going to do everything I possibly can especially because I even got a ticket for having dark tinted headlight covers which was sold to us that way, the officer even put on the ticket that the dealer should've never sold the vehicle that way and we also found out that there's a recall on the vehicles airbags, wow, I'm glad the vehicle is parked for now, it's a dangerous situation to be in if we were in a accident in a vehicle with recalled airbags<//review>

< userid>
114241137015833586621</userid>
<text>DO NOT BUY FROM THIS PLACE!!! My family and I found a 2007 GMC Denali that this place had "on sale" with 14x,xxx miles and were asking $16k in person (even though online price was $14.7k). A little high for the price, but it was the type of SUV we were looking for and looked alright online...

We test drove the Yukon with the salesman, which I will say was very nice at first, and I was able to instantly tell the Yukon needed tires (worn out and feathering), an alignment (possibly needing steering components too), coolant flush, brake rotors (worn with grooves), and based on shifting tendencies... a transmission flush as well. We got back from our test drive and all other sales guys were just chillin by the wheelchair ramp smoking as we walked by with our 3mo old baby givin some  nasty looks to myself and my wife.

Got inside to "see the manager" and began the tedious and exhausting process of negotiating with these people. I agreed that the price they were asking would be fair based on KBB values for dealer pricing based on other Denalis in the area... ONLY if they would at the very least perform a trans service and install NEW tires. The "manager" and salesman went into their little office... which isnt really soundproof... and could hear them calling "the boss" and could hear them saying "yea, we got this f**ker if you put some used tires on"...

Alright, I'll let the "f**ker" comment go for now because we wanted the car, but here's the problem, a 2007 Yukon Denali is AWD... for those not so mechanically inclined... when you replace one tire on an AWD car/truck, you MUST replace all if them with NEW tires of the same design, otherwise you WILL cause road vibrations, drivetrain issues, premature vehicle wear, or even worse with used tires... and that is a safety concern, especially for 2 new parents...

The "manager" says "the boss says we'll put on 4 new USED tires, but thats it"... to which I responded "you do know that is a safety concern right? And we have a baby..." and he tries to play it off as if Im stupid and that the used tires would be fine and that I "clearly dont know about cars, and used tires are totally safe on AWD cars..."

What he didnt know is hes talking to an ex military aircraft maintenance technician with 13+ years in aircraft and automotive repair experience, and a previous automotive service advisor for a dealer-quality shop in the valley, and that this was NOT my first used car purchase, and that I unquestionably knew more about the car they were selling than they did. I insisted on all new tires and a trans flush and he comes back and says "all he's willing to do is new tires" but nothing else...

I mention the brakes, the trans, coolant, and alignment once more, all the while my wife and I both hear the salesguy outside chatting with the other salesguys about how "i got this sale"... We talk with the manager a few more minutes about how the owner thinks its ok to put used tires on AWD cares and selling cars with bad brakes and how their "quality inspection" "always verifies vehicles before they are put on sale"... he proceeds to tell me "well if you dont buy it, someone else will..." Absolutely disgusted, we left and now will spread the word about this place...

They are aweful. Not only are the vehicles garbage, the staff shady and rude, the parking nonexistant, the owner MIA and sounding like a money-hungry A-typical used carlot owner, but their detail department must be ran by Helen Keller (all cars smelled aweful, swirls in paint, stains and dirt everywhere, and waterspots everywhere). Thank god we did not buy from this place and Godspeed to those who do. Based on other reviews, I can see why people dont come here... and as for all the positive reviews on here, go ahead and read through them... they all start to sound the same and more like a commercial rather than a review. Highly suspect they are having fam and friends or fake accounts put up over-glorified reviews to cancel out the truthful reviews here.< /text></record>

< Review>
I myself purchased 3 clones from these guys and two of the two red dragons that i purchased were male. The third was a maui and i have to say she is doing quite well. Now, she was in the middle of the two outside on my back porch getting some sun and somehow according to these folks my dragons got laid but my maui didn't. Mmmmm. Don't figure to me.
